Mapping Texas Parks

This is an example of plotting data from TXPWD. The Gould Eco Regions data can be found here.

Load sf.

library(tidyverse)
library(sf)

Read in the shapefile.

ger <- st_read("GouldEcoRegions.shp") %>% st_simplify(dTolerance = 1e3)

Look the Coordinate Reference System. Its the Texas State Mapping System.

st_crs(ger)
## Coordinate Reference System:
##   No EPSG code
##   proj4string: "+proj=lcc +lat_1=27.41666666666667 +lat_2=34.91666666666666 +lat_0=31.16666666666667 +lon_0=-100 +x_0=1000000 +y_0=1000000 +datum=NAD83 +units=m +no_defs"

We can plot using the sf plot function.

if (compareVersion(as.character(packageVersion("ggplot2")), "2.2.1") < 1)
  devtools::install_github("hadley/ggplot2")
library(ggplot2)
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = ger, aes(fill = Shape_Area)) -> er.plot
er.plot

er.plot + geom_sf(data = st_centroid(ger), color = "red")
## Warning in st_centroid.sf(ger): st_centroid assumes attributes are constant
## over geometries of x

Read in park boundaries

parks <- st_read("TPWDStateParksBoundary.shp") %>% st_simplify(dTolerance = 1e3)
## Reading layer `TPWDStateParksBoundary' from data source `/Users/tkeitt/Dropbox/R/keitt.ssi.2019/inst/materials/examples/TXPWD Ecoregions/TPWDStateParksBoundary.shp' using driver `ESRI Shapefile'

With buffering and alpha, we can create a halo around parks to make small polygons more visible.

er.plot +
  geom_sf(data = st_buffer(parks, 2e4), color = NA, fill = "darkred", alpha = 0.25) +
  geom_sf(data = parks, color = "red", fill = NA)
